[/Desktop]

On a policy level, fossil fuel companies must proactively support high-level initiatives to reduce emissions, including carbon pricing, cap-and-trade, renewable energy standards, renewable fuel standards, and direct emission regulation. By participating constructively and in good faith in policy creation and legislation, corporations can play a role in determining the guidelines and constraints that will eventually enforce future green business practices.

Climate change disproportionately affects poor, marginalized, and politically disenfranchised communities who bear the burden and cost of destruction caused by extreme weather, health issues from food shortages and heat stress, and environmental displacement. Fossil fuel corporations must pay reparations to divert historical profits from irreparably harming the environment to those who are currently most affected and least able to afford the catastrophic costs of climate change.

In the interest of envisioning a carbon-free future, fossil fuel companies should support and fund science and technological research into alternative energy technologies, carbon abatement technology, and other green technology solutions to ensure that their bottom line is not dependent on perpetuating outdated and dangerous forms of energy production.

Finally, corporations must update financial models to plan for a low-carbon future and a divestment from fossil fuels. It is in the interest of investors and the public that fossil fuel companies disclose the risks and future costs that climate change poses to the world at large, and by proxy their own businesses.

Borrowing the visual language of educational posters showing individual tips for reducing emissions, we have helpfully compiled these demands into the following interactive graphic. We hope that it provides a useful roadmap to the fossil fuel executives, boards of directors, and investors who are responsible for their corporations' enormous historic CO₂ emissions.

